agentctl — licensing
=====================

This repository is licensed under TWO licenses, by component. Each crate
declares its license in its `Cargo.toml` (`license = ...`); this file is the
authoritative map.

Apache License 2.0  (open source — see LICENSE-APACHE)
------------------------------------------------------
The contract (the standard), the SDK/libraries, and the client tooling are
permissively licensed so that ANY agent vendor or integrator can implement and
use them freely (the contract must be open to be a standard):

  - contract/                      (the Agent Control Contract: schemas + fixtures + spec)
  - crates/agent-api               (Agent / AgentFleet / ModelPool / MCPServerSet CRD types)
  - crates/agent-contract-client   (the typed contract client / SDK)
  - crates/agentctl-cli            (the CLI / kubectl plugin)
  - crates/agentctl-crdgen         (CRD YAML generator)
  - crates/mock-agent              (conformant-agent stand-in for dev/conformance)

Business Source License 1.1  (source-available — see LICENSE-BUSL)
------------------------------------------------------------------
The runnable control plane is under the BUSL. You may read, modify, and make
non-production and internal non-commercial use of it freely; commercial
production use or offering it as a hosted/managed service requires a commercial
license until the Change Date (2030-06-28), on which each version converts to
Apache License 2.0. See LICENSE-BUSL for the exact terms and Additional Use
Grant.

  - crates/agentctl-operator
  - crates/agentctl-apiserver
  - crates/agentctl-gateway
  - crates/agentctl-modelgateway
  - crates/agentctl-mcpgateway
  - crates/agentctl-admission
  - crates/agentctl-coordination
  - crates/agentctl-scaler
  - crates/agentctl-telemetry

Commercial licensing: andrii@tsok.org

Contributions are accepted under the Contributor License Agreement (see CLA.md),
which lets the project offer the dual (open-source / commercial) licensing above.

Note: "Business Source License" components are source-available, not OSI
"open source," until their Change Date. The Apache-2.0 components are open source.
